In [ ]:
sns.heatmap(df.corr(), annot = True, cmap='YlGnBu');

A multivariate analysis is based in observation and analysis of more than one statistical outcome variable at a time. In design and analysis, the technique is used to perform trade studies across multiple dimensions while taking into account the effects of all variables on the responses of interest. As we can observe through the correlation chart and heatmap, most of the variables do not have much correlation amongst each other. The variables have either low or negative correlations amongst each other meaning they are not invertly directed with one another and so the data is random. This could be due to the abundance random outcome of variables in the data and so it is hard to configure a correlation. If we were to look at the heatmap, the data correlation is givin a vizualization. In a heat map, an individual square contains the correlations between two data variables, the darker the square the greater the correlation, the lighter the less. In the heat map, it can be observed there is a lack of correlation between the variables, and in some instances there are negative correlations. In conclusion, the multivariate analysis determines there is little to negative correlation between the data variables.

When we first input the code, there is an error. 'Ratings' is not an interger, but instead an object data type and we have to convert the category into a float data type.

Python is indicating there are values 'not given' but python computes this into an object and we have to convert the 'not given' value into a nan variable.

In [21]:
df['rating']=df['rating'].replace(['Not given'], np.nan)

This function allows to replace the 'Not given' value to nan.

In [22]:
df['rating'] = df['rating'].astype(float)

Following the function, command python to convery the data type from an object to float, hence creating the data set into an interger.

Conclusion: The purpose of this study was to provide an analysis for a food delivery app, focusing in New York. The app Food Hub, allows customers to order food from local restaurants and have it delivered. This app is convienent for New York due to the hectic life of the city. It could be concluded there is a lack of data correlation between the variables, and so it would be difficult to find correlation. Though, it must said there are restaurants and cuisines that are more popular than others, in particular American restaurants. Now, it makes sense in New York, American is the most popular due to location and familairity, but there are other factors for other cuisines. The multivariate analysis confirms there is a lack of correlation between the two variables, ratings, food time cooked and delivered, does not determine the amount of business brought to the business, but there are recommendations.

Recommendations: The first recommendation is to observe the cuisine type with the least amount of business. Presented below those businesses do not have a consistent food prep and delivery time. There is a limited amount of restaurants that provide these specific cuisines, and in order to drive business the app must provide a promotion for these establishments in order to drive sales. The app should require a certain percentage of their sales in order to promote their restaurants. Every week or Food Hub should select Thai for example and tell customers they will eliminate their delivery charge if they order from Thai restaurants. Focus goes towards Thai, sales go up, there is a greater familirarity with the product. Increase the sales number, this will increase the consistency of the times, and consistency will create a larger customer base.
